    "summary": "The Aksumite Empire at its peak (c. 100–600 AD) was one of the four great powers of the ancient world — alongside Rome, Persia, and China — as described by the contemporary Persian text Mani's writing. Centered in the Ethiopian highlands with its capital at Aksum (in modern Tigray), the empire controlled not only the northern Horn of Africa but also significant territory in southern Arabia (modern Yemen), which it conquered and periodically held during this period. Aksum's control of the Red Sea — the critical shipping corridor connecting the Mediterranean world with India and East Africa — made it a major commercial power.\n\nAksum's ports, particularly Adulis on the Red Sea, were cosmopolitan trading hubs where merchants from Rome, Persia, India, and Arabia exchanged goods. The empire exported ivory, gold, incense, and exotic animals to the Mediterranean world; it imported luxury textiles, wine, and manufactured goods. Aksumite coins — gold, silver, and bronze — were among the most widely circulated currencies in the Red Sea region and evidence of sophisticated state organization. The empire's [[event:2064|adoption of Christianity]] under Ezana gave it an alliance with Byzantine Rome against the Sassanid Persian sphere. The empire's decline came gradually in the 7th century, as Arab Muslim expansion across Arabia disrupted the Red Sea trade networks on which Aksumite prosperity depended, shifting commerce away from Adulis and inland. By the 8th century, the empire had contracted to its Ethiopian core.",
